        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Feb. 26</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have not strength from ill-health to discuss the point raised in your letter.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I do not think the difficulty is greater for evolution than for ordinary growth. Every organism is developed from a single cell. Look at a man with an additional &amp; abnormal finger   here we see new bones formed. I am much obliged for your kind offer to send me the book, but I do not care to see it.—</p>
<p>Dear Sir | yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9282.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from W. T. Goodale, 11 February 1874</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In his <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9282.xml" resp="#automat" cert="low">letter to CD of 11 February 1874</ref>, Goodale had queried an objection to development theory raised in Mark <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3842.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Hopkins 1873</ref>, and based on the observation that no bone of the skeleton came into direct contact with any other bones; since they, and other systems, could not have grown from a single point, they must (if development theory were true) have all existed in a single cell, which <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2379.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Mark Hopkins</ref> took to be impossible.</note>
        </div>        
            
